{{Infobox Weapon|is_vehicle=yes | name = Panzerjäger Tiger (P) image = caption = The United | States Army Ordnance Museum's restored Elefant. type = Heavy | tank destroyer origin = Nazi Germany | designer= Dr. Ferdinand Porsche design_date= 1942–1943 manufacturer= Porsche | AG production_date= March–May 1943
(modification into Elefant | October–November 1943) number= 91 | length = with gun width = height = weight = suspension = | longitudinal torsion-bar speed = vehicle_range = road
cross- | country primary_armament = 8.8 cm Pak 43/2 L/71, also known as | StuK 43/1 secondary_armament = 7.92 mm MG 34 machine gun (only | Elefant) armour = 200 mm (7.87 in) engine = 2 × Maybach HL 120 | petrol crew = 6 (driver, radio-operator, commander, gunner, two | loaders) engine_power = 600 PS (592 hp, 442 kW) pw_ratio = 9.23 | PS/tonne }} 'Elefant' (German for "elephant") was a Schwerer [[Panzerjäger]] ("heavy tank destroyer") of the German [[Wehrmacht]] used in small numbers in World War II. It was built in 1943 under the name 'Ferdinand', after its designer Ferdinand Porsche. In 1944, after modification of the existing vehicles, they were renamed Elefant. The official German designation was 'Panzerjäger Tiger(P)' and the ordnance inventory designation was 'Sd. Kfz.184'.
